The original purpose of SFINAE is to solve a critical problem--if you have multiple template versions of a function available, they don&#x27;t all have to be valid for a given call. For example say you want to have a &quot;first&quot; operator that takes the first item of a container, but also works on individual values if they aren&#x27;t containers:<p>template<class Container>
Container::value_type first(Container&& c) {
  return *c.begin();
}<p>template<class ValueType>
ValueType first(ValueType&& vt) {
  return vt;
}<p>// Usage:
first<int>(1); // 1<p>This call doesn&#x27;t cause a compile error even though int::value_type does not exist--this is SFINAE. To make this work properly you&#x27;d also need to use compile-time introspection to disable the second function for types that have value_type, otherwise it&#x27;s ambiguous.
